A 9-year-old boy with a history of severe necrotizing pancreatitis underwent endoscopic transgastric drainage of a mature pancreatic pseudocyst with stent placement. On postoperative day 4, he develops acute abdominal pain, hematemesis, hypotension, and a hemoglobin drop from 11 to 7 g/dL. Imaging reveals cyst enlargement with hyperdense contents and proximity to the splenic artery. What is the most likely complication?\
\
A. Leak with perforation  \
B. Infection of the pseudocyst  \
C. Hemorrhage from pseudoaneurysm  \
D. Postprocedure pancreatitis  \
E. Recurrent pseudocyst due to stent obstruction  \
\
<!-- EXPLANATION -->\
\
### Overview of Complications After Pseudocyst Drainage in Pediatric Pancreatitis\
Pseudocyst drainage, whether endoscopic or surgical, carries risks influenced by technique, cyst maturity, and underlying pancreatic pathology. Mature walls reduce leak risks, but necrosis increases hemorrhage potential. Complications include leak/perforation, infection, hemorrhage, postprocedure pancreatitis, and recurrence/incomplete drainage. Endoscopic approaches report 8-10% recurrence; surgical hemostatic sutures minimize bleeding.\
\
#### Major Complications and Mechanisms\
- **Leak/Perforation**: Occurs shortly post-procedure or during stent exchange; small leaks managed conservatively, larger require reintervention. Mature walls mitigate risk.\
- **Infection**: Introduces bacteria during drainage; presents with fever, leukocytosis; treated with antibiotics or additional drainage.\
- **Hemorrhage**: Mild to severe; often from cyst erosion into vessels (gastroduodenal, pancreaticoduodenal, splenic arteries) forming pseudoaneurysms, especially in necrotizing pancreatitis. Requires endoscopy, angiography, or surgery; electrocautery prevents during procedures.\
- **Postprocedure Pancreatitis**: In 5-10% of cases; due to manipulation irritating parenchyma; managed supportively.\
- **Recurrence/Incomplete Drainage**: 8-10% post-endoscopy (stent obstruction, duct stricture); similar surgically from ongoing disease. Requires reimaging and repeat intervention.\
